SIMPLE: regard
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Regard
<hw>Re*gard"</hw> <pr>(r?*g?rd")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Regarded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Regarding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>regarder</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re + <ets>garder</ets> to
guard, heed, keep. See <er>Guard</er>, and cf. <er>Reward</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To keep in view; to behold; to look at; to view; to
gaze upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your niece <qex>regards</qex> me with an eye of favor.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to look or front toward; to face.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is peninsula which <qex>regardeth</qex> the mainland.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That exceedingly beatiful seat, on the ascent of a hill, flanked
with wood and <qex>regarding</qex> the river.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To look closely at; to observe attentively; to pay
attention to; to notice or remark particularly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If much you note him,⟦br⟧
You offened him; . . . feed, and <qex>regard</qex> him not.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To look upon, as in a certain relation; to hold as
an popinion; to consider; <as>as, to <ex>regard</ex> abstinence from
wine as a duty; to <ex>regard</ex> another as a friend or
enemy.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To consider and treat; to have a certain feeling
toward; <as>as, to <ex>regard</ex> one with favor or
dislike</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His associates seem to have <qex>regarded</qex> him with
kindness.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To pay respect to; to treat as something of peculiar
value, sanctity, or the like; to care for; to esteem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that <qex>regardeth</qex> thae day, <qex>regardeth</qex> it
into the LOrd.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xiv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here's Beaufort, that <qex>regards</qex> nor God nor king.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To take into consideration; to take account of, as a
fact or condition.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Nether <xex>regarding</xex> that she is
my child, nor fearing me as if II were her father.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To have relation to, as bearing upon; to respect; to
relate to; to touch; <as>as, an argument does not <ex>regard</ex> the
question</as>; -- often used impersonally; <as>as, I agree with you as
<ex>regards</ex> this or that</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To consider; observe; remark; heed; mind;
respect; esteem; estimate; value. See <er>Attend</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Regard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Regard
<hw>Re*gard"</hw> <pr>(r?*g?rd")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To look
attentively; to consider; to notice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Regard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Regard
<hw>Re*gard"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>regard</ets> See
<er>Regard</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A look; aspect
directed to another; view; gaze.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But her, with stern <qex>regard</qex>, he thus repelled.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Attention of the mind with a feeling of interest;
observation; heed; notice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full many a lady⟦br⟧
I have eyed with best <qex>regard</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That view of the mind which springs from perception
of value, estimable qualities, or anything that excites admiration;
respect; esteem; reverence; affection; <as>as, to have a high
<ex>regard</ex> for a person</as>; -- often in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He has rendered himself worthy of their most favorable
<qex>regards</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>A. Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Save the long-sought <qex>regards</qex> of woman, nothing is
sweeter than those marks of childish preference.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>State of being regarded, whether favorably or
otherwise; estimation; repute; note; account.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man of meanest <qex>regard</qex> amongst them, neither having
wealth or power.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Consideration; thought; reflection; heed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sad pause and deep <qex>regard</qex> become the sage.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Matter for consideration; account; condition.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Reason full of good <xex>regard</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Respect; relation; reference.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Persuade them to pursue and persevere in virtue, with
<qex>regard</qex> to themselves; in justice and goodness with
<qex>regard</qex> to their neighbors; and piefy toward God.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The phrase <xex>in regard of</xex> was formerly used as
equivalent in meaning to <xex>on account of</xex>, but in modern usage
is often improperly substituted for <xex>in respect to</xex>, or <xex>in
regard to</xex>.</note> <rj><au>G. P. Marsh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Change was thought necessary <qex>in regard of</qex> the injury
the church did receive by a number of things then in use.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>In regard of</qex> its security, it had a great advantage
over the bandboxes.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Object of sight; scene; view; aspect.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Throw out our eyes for brave Othello,⟦br⟧
Even till we make the main and the aerial blue⟦br⟧
An indistinct <qex>regard</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(O.Eng.Law)</fld> <def>Supervision;
inspection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At regard of</b></col>, <cd>in consideration of; in
comparison with.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Bodily penance is but
short and little <xex>at regard of</xex> the pains of hell.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Court of regard</b></col>, <cd>a forest
court formerly held in England every third year for the lawing, or
expeditation, of dogs, to prevent them from running after deer; --
called also <altname>survey of dogs</altname>.</cd>
<au>Blackstone.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Respect; consideration; notice; observance; heed;
care; concern; estimation; esteem; attachment; reverence.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Regardable</ent>⟦br⟧
